Water is also known as "the universal solvent" because almost all substances will dissolve in water, with some exceptions like oil and gasoline which do not mix well with water. The properties of water make it ideal for many industrial processes including cleaning, cooling, heating, lubrication, chemical reactions, and more. Its ability to dissolve so much makes it very useful. Water can be used in various ways due to its physical or chemical property:
1) Water can be boiled to generate steam, which can then drive turbines that produce electricity;
2) Heat from the sun drives evaporation of seawater (or any freshwater lake), where wind carries away the moist air into clouds forming rain drops falling back onto earth again. These raindrops are heavier than air and thus sink down towards lower levels until they fall out at sea level again after having lost energy on their way down. This process is driven by heat and pressure differences between ocean surface and atmosphere, but also by temperature gradients inside the cloud itself;
3) In nature plants grow using carbon dioxide from the soil via stomata openings in the leaf epidermis. They release oxygen during this procedure. This exchange is possible thanks to water molecules moving across cell membranes allowing gaseous exchange while preventing liquid diffusion;
