 There are many ways you can descend from a cliff, depending on what is available in your environment:
  * If there is any kind of vegetation growing near the base of the cliff (such as bushes or trees), climb down using their branches or trunks;
  * Use rope to lower yourself down;
  * Build an inclined ramp out of rocks, sand, snow, etc.;
  * Jump off the ledge into a body of water far below if it is deep enough for you not to injure yourself too badly upon landing;
  * Abseil, which involves descending by tying one end of a rope around your waist while holding onto the other end with both hands. You then slide down along this rope at high speed until reaching the desired depth level. This method works well only when the ground underneath has some solidity and stability so that abseiling does not become dangerous due to instability issues. A fall may cause injury even if absorbed partially by the harness system. However, falling over large heights will always be fatal because there won't be time enough for deployment of parachutes before impact occurs.

Depends on how much time you have left, but these options should work pretty good!</s>

