 The difficulty of understanding the Tsugaru dialect can be attributed primarily to phonological differences from Standard Japanese. Specifically, there are a number of sounds in the language that do not exist or differ significantly from those found in standard Japanese:
- Pronunciation of "u" as [ɯ] (or as an unaspirated version of [ɸ]) instead of [ɯ], which results in words like "taberu" and "tadori" sounding quite different when compared with their counterparts in standard Japanese;
- Pharyngealization of certain consonants, such as palatalizing [k] into [c] and [ts] into [sʲ];
- Lack of contrast between long /e/ and short /o/, resulting in homophones such as kokoro and koyori having distinct meanings;
- In some cases, pronouncing vowels differently than they would be pronounced in other Japanese dialects. For example, in Aomori Prefecture, where the Tsugaru dialect originates, people may say "hito" for "hitobito," meaning "person." While this word differs slightly from how it's said in Tokyo, it wouldn't be confused for anything else. Similarly, if someone were speaking Osaka dialect, they might call themselves Ōsakazuke for Ōsakazoku - but since all three names have similarities, it could take multiple listens before one realizes what was meant by any given name.
All these examples should give you a good idea on why this dialect is considered difficult even among natives! If I missed something feel free to ask again ;)</s>

