Big-O Notation, also known as Landau Symbols or Order of Growth Notation, refers to a way of describing the growth rate (or asymptotic complexity) of an algorithm. It allows us to compare different algorithms and make informed decisions about which one will be faster for our particular problem.
The symbols used in Big-O Notation are: Ω, o(), and Θ. They describe how fast a function grows compared with another function when both functions grow at similar rates. Here's a simple example using arithmetic operations:
```c++
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;
int main() {
    int n = 50; // The number we want to square
    cout << "Squaring integers up to N takes " << o((n^2)) << endl;
}
```
Here, `o` means that `n^2 <= k * m`, where `k > 0`. This is true if you can divide by any constant factor without changing its value, like `m / 10 == m/100`, so `o()` describes a set of numbers close enough together to fit inside some fixed interval. For this reason it doesn't matter whether `n` or `N` has a larger absolute value than each other - they just need to be sufficiently large to allow dividing out common factors. So squaring integers from zero through fifty requires two multiplications, while going above five hundred requires three. Therefore the running time for this operation on all integers less than 5000 would be `(3*49 + 2*(50+49))/(60*60) ~= 7 seconds`. And because squared numbers always get bigger more quickly then squares, there'd still only be seven seconds even if the maximum input were 1 billion! In general, `x^(y)` will

