Self attention can be viewed as an efficient way to compute a set of linear transformations on each feature vector without explicitly storing them in memory beforehand. It is also possible (though not necessarily practical) to implement it efficiently using a matrix multiplication. 

In general, we want our attention mechanism to have two key qualities: 1.) Efficient computation for large inputs, 2.) Flexibility in how much contextual information you would like to take into account when calculating the final transformation.

The original Transformer paper introduces three different variants of attention mechanisms that satisfy these criteria while being easy to understand intuitively at first glance:
\begin{itemize}
\item Linear Attenation - This variant simply computes the dot product between the query vector $Q$ and all other vectors from the input. It's simple but very expensive since its computational complexity grows exponentially with the size of the vocabulary $|V|$.
\end{itemize}

